                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18181028-85-off496 t18181028-85-crimeloc499"></join>, about nine o'clock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18181028-85-person633">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MARDLING
               <interp inst="t18181028-85-person633" type="surname" value="MARDLING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18181028-85-person633" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18181028-85-person633" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in Smithfield with my waggon, and saw the officer with the coat; I said it was the prosecutor's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18181028-85-person634">
                  JOHN 
                  HARKER
               <interp inst="t18181028-85-person634" type="surname" value="HARKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18181028-85-person634" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18181028-85-person634" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw the prisoner walk away with the coat. I asked him what it was? He said "Only my boy's coat." I asked him to show me his boy. He took me to the Ram Inn-yard, and then said it was not the place. He then took me to the Rose, and said I might have the coat, for he found it.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I found it between two waggons.</p>
               <p>
